iation football goalkeepers]]\n\n{{Colombia-footy-goalkeeper-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=November 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox football biography| name= Brayan L\u00f3pez\n| image =\n| fullname = Brayan Styven L\u00f3pez Yepes<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/bryan-stiven-lopez/22481/|title=Colombia - B. L\u00f3pez - Profile with news, career statistics and history - Soccerway|website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1987|6|25|df=y}}<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n| birth_place = [[Medell\u00edn]], [[Colombia]]<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n| height = 185 cm\n| currentclub  = [[Independiente Medell\u00edn]]\n| clubnumber = 1\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n|  years1 =   2006 \u2013 2008<sup>1</sup> \n| years2 =   2008  \n| years3 =   2009 \u2013\n|  clubs1 =   [[Independiente Medell\u00edn]] \n| clubs2 =  [[Atl\u00e9tico Bucaramanga]] \n| clubs3 =  [[Independiente Medell\u00edn]]\n| caps1 =    57  \n| caps2 =   18  \n| caps3 =    5  \n| goals1 =  0  \n| goals2 =  0  \n| goals3 =  0 \n| nationalyears1 =   \n| nationalteam1 =   \n| nationalcaps1 =     \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| pcupdate = 21:05, 21 March 2010 (UTC) }}\n\n'''Brayan Styven L\u00f3pez Yepes''' (born 25 June 1987 in [[Medell\u00edn]]) is a [[Colombia]]n [[Association football|footballer]]. He currently plays as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[Independiente Medell\u00edn]] in the [[Copa Mustang]].\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bdfa.com.ar/jugadores-BRYAN-STIVEN-LOPEZ-45607.html BDFA profile] {{in lang|es}}\n* {{ESPN FC|118985}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lopez, Brayan}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Colombian footballers]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Medell\u00edn]]\n[[Category:Independiente Medell\u00edn footballers]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Bucaramanga footballers]]\n[[Category:Categor\u00eda Primera A players]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n\n{{Colombia-footy-goalkeeper-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Colombian footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Colombian footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brayan_L%C3%B3pez"}
{"title_page": "John Hejduk", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person/Wikidata | fetchwikidata=ALL | onlysourced=yes}}\n\n'''John Quentin Hejduk''' (19 July 1929 \u2013 3 July 2000) was an American architect, artist and educator of [[Czechs|Czech]] origin who spent much of his life in [[New York City]], United States. Hejduk is noted for having had a profound interest in the fundamental issues of shape, organization, representation, and reciprocity.\n\nHejduk studied at the [[Cooper Union School of Art and Architecture]], the [[University of Cincinnati]], and the [[Harvard Graduate School of Design]]. He worked in several offices in New York including that of [[I. M. Pei]] and Partners and the office of A.M. Kinney and Associates. He established his own practice in New York City in 1965.<ref name=\"GreatBuildings\">{{cite web  |url=http://www.greatbuildings.com/architects/John_Hejduk.html/\n|publisher=Great Buildings Collection |title=John Hejduk |accessdate=18 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n===As a professor===\nHejduk was Professor of Architecture at [[Cooper Union|The Cooper Union for the Advancement of Science and Art, School of Architecture]] from 1964 to 2000 and Dean of the School of Architecture from 1975 to 2000. His arrival including the cooperation of many other influential professors (including [[Raimund Abraham]], [[Ricardo Scofidio]], [[Peter Eisenman]], [[Charles Gwathmey]], [[Diana Agrest]], Diane Lewis, [[Elizabeth Diller]], [[David Shapiro (poet)|David Shapiro]], Don Wall and many others) transformed the practice and critical thought of architecture in ways that might be compared to [[Ludwig Mies Van Der Rohe]]'s transformation of the Armour Institute into the [[Illinois Institute of Technology]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n\n==Approach==\nHis early work and curriculum grew from a set of exercises exploring cubes, grids, and frames, through an examination of square grids placed within diagonal containers set against an occasional curving wall, towards a series of experiments with flat planes and curved masses in various combinations and colors.<ref name=\"GreatBuildings\"/> To aid his research he was awarded a grant from the Graham Foundation in 1967. Eventually, John Hejduk's \"hard-line\" modernist space-making exercises, heavily influenced by [[Frank Lloyd Wright]] and [[Ludwig Mies Van Der Rohe]], moved away from his interests in favor of free-hand \"figure/objects\" influenced by mythology and spirituality, clearly expressing the nature of his poetry.{{Citation needed|date=October 2013}}  The relationship between Hejduk's shape/objects and their surroundings is a controversial subject, raising questions similar to those raised by the early houses of [[Peter Eisenman]].\n\nThe architectural historian K. Michael Hays has described Hejduk's architecture as one of \"Encounter\", describing Hejduk's objects as seeming \"impossibly, to be aware of us, to address us. And yet we see not the gratifying reflection of ourselves we had hoped for but another thing, looking back at us, watching us, placing us\", articulating Hejduk's work from a post-modern Lacanian perspective as more \"literary\" than that of his peers. <ref>{{Cite book|title=Architecture's Desire|last=Hays|first=K. Michael|publisher=The MIT Press|year=2010|isbn=978-0-262-51302-9|location=55 Hayward Street, Cambridge MA 02142|pages=90}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nHejduk is associated with several schools, including the [[The New York Five|New York Five]] (with architects [[Peter Eisenman]], [[Richard Meier]], [[Michael Graves]], and [[Charles Gwathmey]]) whose early works are described in ''Five Architects'' (1973),<ref name=Goldberger>{{cite journal| author=Goldberger, Paul | title =Architecture View: A Little Book That Led Five Men to Fame | journal =[[The New York Times]] | volume = | issue = | pages = | publisher = | location =| date =February 11, 1996| url =https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9505E2DB1539F932A25751C0A960958260&sec=&spon=&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink| accessdate =August 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author =Iovine, Julie V. | title =Michael Graves | publisher =Chronicle Books | series = | volume = | edition = | year =2000 | location =San Francisco | pages =[https://archive.org/details/michaelgraves00iovi/page/9 9\u201310] | url =https://archive.org/details/michaelgraves00iovi/page/9 | isbn =0-8118-3251-1 | url-access =registration }}</ref> and the [[Texas Rangers (architects)|Texas Rangers]], a group of innovative architects and professors at the Texas School of Architecture, [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], whose other well-known participants include [[Colin Rowe]] and [[Werner Seligmann]].\n\nContemporary theorists, researchers, and academics publishing work and research by and about John Hejduk include [[K. Michael Hays]],<ref>{{cite book|first=K. Michael|last=Hays|title=Sanctuaries: The Last Works of John Hejduk|publisher=Harry N. Abrams |work=Whitney Museum|date=April 1, 2003|isbn=978-0-8742-7129-4}}</ref> [[Mark Linder]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Nothing Less than Literal: Architecture after Minimalism|first=Mark |last=Linder|date=February 4, 2005|publisher=The MIT Press|isbn=978-0-2621-2266-5}}</ref> [[R.E. Somol]],<ref>{{cite journal|title=Exhibition: Other Soundings: selected works by John Hejduk 1954-1997: a review (in Japanese and English)|author1=Somol, Robert |author2=Shubert, Howard |work=A+U: Architecture and Urbanism|number=327| date=December 1997|pages=3\u201313}}</ref> [[Anthony Vidler]]<ref>{{cite book|first=Anthony |last=Vidler|title=The Architectural Uncanny: Essays in the Modern Unhomely|publisher=The MIT Press|edition=First|date=May 8, 1992|isbn=978-0-2622-2044-6}}</ref> and [[Renata Hejduk]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Religious Imagination in Modern and Contemporary Architecture: A Reader \n|editor=Renata Hejduk|publisher=Routledge|date=February 17, 2011|isbn=978-0-4157-8080-3|display-editors=etal}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nA large portion of his work is archived at the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] in [[Montreal, Quebec]].\n\n== Important buildings ==\n*House For a Musician (1983)\n*House of the Suicide and House of the Mother of the Suicide (Prague, monument installed 2016)\n*Kreuzberg Tower and Wings (Berlin, Allemagne, 1988)\n*Tegel Housing (Berlin, 1988)\n*House of the Quadruplets / House for two Brothers (Berlin, Tegel, 1988)\n*Gate House (Berlin, 1991) for the IBA 87\n*La M\u00e1scara de la Medusa (Buenos Aires, 1998)\n*[[Wall House II]] (Groningen, 2001)\n\n<gallery heights=\"180\" widths=\"180\" caption=\"Important buildings of John Hejduk\">\nFile:HejdukKreuzbergTower1.jpg|Kreuzberg Tower and Wings<br /> (Berlin, Germany, 1988).\nFile:HejdukKreuzbergTower2.jpg|Kreuzberg Tower and Wings<br /> (Berlin, Germany, 1988).\nFile:Wall House2.JPG|Wall House [[Wall House II|II]]<br /> design from the 1970s, built posthumously (Groningen, The Netherlands, 2001).\nFile:2013. Torres Hejduk. Cidade da Cultura. Santiago de Compostela - Galiza-2.jpg|In [[Santiago de Compostela]], Spain.\n</gallery>\n\n=== The Rolling House ===\nIn 2019, students of the Faculty of Architecture of the [[Czech Technical University]] in Prague led by Hana Seho built the object ''The Rolling House'' according to drawings by John Hejduk. The project was created in the studio during the Summer School of Building on the topic of minimal mobile building. The realization took place in October and November 2019. The building was unveiled on 11 November 2019 as a celebration of the 30th anniversary of the [[Velvet Revolution]] and as a gift to [[Alena \u0160r\u00e1mkov\u00e1]] for her 90th birthday.<ref>{{cite web\n |url= https://aktualne.cvut.cz/tiskove-zpravy/20191115-studenti-a-pedagogove-fakulty-architektury-cvut-v-praze-dali-alene-sramkove\n |title= Studenti a pedagogov\u00e9 Fakulty architektury \u010cVUT v Praze dali Alen\u011b \u0160r\u00e1mkov\u00e9 k narozenin\u00e1m d\u016fm na kole\u010dk\u00e1ch \n |last= Rottov\u00e1\n |first= Kate\u0159ina \n |date= 2019-11-15\n |website= aktualne.cvut.cz\n |publisher= Czech Technical University in Prague\n |access-date= 2019-11-17\n |quote= }}</ref>\n\n== Conceptual Works ==\n\n* Diamond Houses (1962)\n* Identity Card Man (Victim Series, 1986)\n* Cemetery for the Ashes of Thought (1975) \n* Berlin Masque (1981)\n* Cathedral (1996) \n* Chapel, Wedding of the Sun and Moon (1998)\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''Lines: No Fire Could Burn'' (1999)\n* ''Education Of An Architect A Point Of View'' (1988, 1999)\n* ''Pewter Wings Golden Horns Stone Veils: Wedding in a Dark Plum Room'' (1997)\n* ''Adjusting Foundations'' (1995)\n* ''Architectures In Love'' (1995)\n* ''Security'' (1995)\n* ''Berlin Night'' (1993)\n* ''Soundings'' (1993)\n* ''Aesop's Fables'' with Joseph Jacobs. Illustrations by John Hejduk. (1991)\n* ''Pr\u00e1ce (Practice)'' (1991)\n* ''The Riga Project'' (1989)\n* ''Vladivostok'' (1989)\n* ''Bovisa'' (1987)\n* ''Victims'' (1986)\n* ''Mask of Medusa'' (1985)\n* ''Fabrications'' (1974)\n* ''Three Projects'' (1969)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|John Hejduk}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060212211506/http://www.gatech.edu/news-room/release.php?id=21 Georgia Tech Sculptures to Appear in Hejduk Retrospective at Whitney Museum]\n* John Hejduk fonds, [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]]: [https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/archives/381969/john-hejduk-fonds finding aid] / [https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/search?digigroup=381969 digitized items]\n* [http://f-iba.de/wohnhaus-tor-und-uhrenhaus-john-hejduk/]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hejduk, John}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:Architects from New York City]]\n[[Category:Cooper Union alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Cincinnati alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:American architecture writers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Architecture educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American architects]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person/Wikidata | fetchwikidata=ALL | onlysourced=yes}}\n\n'''John Quentin Hejduk''' (19 July 1929 \u2013 3 July 2000) was an American architect, artist and educator of [[Czechs|Czech]] origin who spent much of his life in [[New York City]], United States. Hejduk is noted for having had a profound interest in the fundamental issues of shape, organization, representation, and reciprocity.\n\nHejduk studied at the [[Cooper Union School of Art and Architecture]], the [[University of Cincinnati]], and the [[Harvard Graduate School of Design]]. He worked in several offices in New York including that of [[I. M. Pei]] and Partners and the office of A.M. Kinney and Associates. He established his own practice in New York City in 1965.<ref name=\"GreatBuildings\">{{cite web  |url=http://www.greatbuildings.com/architects/John_Hejduk.html/\n|publisher=Great Buildings Collection |title=John Hejduk |accessdate=18 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n===As a professor===\nHejduk was Professor of Architecture at [[Cooper Union|The Cooper Union for the Advancement of Science and Art, School of Architecture]] from 1964 to 2000 and Dean of the School of Architecture from 1975 to 2000. His arrival including the cooperation of many other influential professors (including [[Raimund Abraham]], [[Ricardo Scofidio]], [[Peter Eisenman]], [[Charles Gwathmey]], [[Diana Agrest]], Diane Lewis, [[Elizabeth Diller]], [[David Shapiro (poet)|David Shapiro]], Don Wall and many others) transformed the practice and critical thought of architecture in ways that might be compared to [[Ludwig Mies Van Der Rohe]]'s transformation of the Armour Institute into the [[Illinois Institute of Technology]].{{Citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n\n==Approach==\nHis early work and curriculum grew from a set of exercises exploring cubes, grids, and frames, through an examination of square grids placed within diagonal containers set against an occasional curving wall, towards a series of experiments with flat planes and curved masses in various combinations and colors.<ref name=\"GreatBuildings\"/> To aid his research he was awarded a grant from the Graham Foundation in 1967. Eventually, John Hejduk's \"hard-line\" modernist space-making exercises, heavily influenced by [[Frank Lloyd Wright]] and [[Ludwig Mies Van Der Rohe]], moved away from his interests in favor of free-hand \"figure/objects\" influenced by mythology and spirituality, clearly expressing the nature of his poetry.{{Citation needed|date=October 2013}}  The relationship between Hejduk's shape/objects and their surroundings is a controversial subject, raising questions similar to those raised by the early houses of [[Peter Eisenman]].\n\nThe architectural historian K. Michael Hays has described Hejduk's architecture as one of \"Encounter\", describing Hejduk's objects as seeming \"impossibly, to be aware of us, to address us. And yet we see not the gratifying reflection of ourselves we had hoped for but another thing, looking back at us, watching us, placing us\", articulating Hejduk's work from a post-modern Lacanian perspective as more \"literary\" than that of his peers. <ref>{{Cite book|title=Architecture's Desire|last=Hays|first=K. Michael|publisher=The MIT Press|year=2010|isbn=978-0-262-51302-9|location=55 Hayward Street, Cambridge MA 02142|pages=90}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nHejduk is associated with several schools, including the [[The New York Five|New York Five]] (with architects [[Peter Eisenman]], [[Richard Meier]], [[Michael Graves]], and [[Charles Gwathmey]]) whose early works are described in ''Five Architects'' (1973),<ref name=Goldberger>{{cite journal| author=Goldberger, Paul | title =Architecture View: A Little Book That Led Five Men to Fame | journal =[[The New York Times]] | volume = | issue = | pages = | publisher = | location =| date =February 11, 1996| url =https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9505E2DB1539F932A25751C0A960958260&sec=&spon=&partner=permalink&exprod=permalink| accessdate =August 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author =Iovine, Julie V. | title =Michael Graves | publisher =Chronicle Books | series = | volume = | edition = | year =2000 | location =San Francisco | pages =[https://archive.org/details/michaelgraves00iovi/page/9 9\u201310] | url =https://archive.org/details/michaelgraves00iovi/page/9 | isbn =0-8118-3251-1 | url-access =registration }}</ref> and the [[Texas Rangers (architects)|Texas Rangers]], a group of innovative architects and professors at the Texas School of Architecture, [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], whose other well-known participants include [[Colin Rowe]] and [[Werner Seligmann]].\n\nContemporary theorists, researchers, and academics publishing work and research by and about John Hejduk include [[K. Michael Hays]],<ref>{{cite book|first=K. Michael|last=Hays|title=Sanctuaries: The Last Works of John Hejduk|publisher=Harry N. Abrams |work=Whitney Museum|date=April 1, 2003|isbn=978-0-8742-7129-4}}</ref> [[Mark Linder]],<ref>{{cite book|title=Nothing Less than Literal: Architecture after Minimalism|first=Mark |last=Linder|date=February 4, 2005|publisher=The MIT Press|isbn=978-0-2621-2266-5}}</ref> [[R.E. Somol]],<ref>{{cite journal|title=Exhibition: Other Soundings: selected works by John Hejduk 1954-1997: a review (in Japanese and English)|author1=Somol, Robert |author2=Shubert, Howard |work=A+U: Architecture and Urbanism|number=327| date=December 1997|pages=3\u201313}}</ref> [[Anthony Vidler]]<ref>{{cite book|first=Anthony |last=Vidler|title=The Architectural Uncanny: Essays in the Modern Unhomely|publisher=The MIT Press|edition=First|date=May 8, 1992|isbn=978-0-2622-2044-6}}</ref> and [[Renata Hejduk]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Religious Imagination in Modern and Contemporary Architecture: A Reader \n|editor=Renata Hejduk|publisher=Routledge|date=February 17, 2011|isbn=978-0-4157-8080-3|display-editors=etal}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nA large portion of his work is archived at the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] in [[Montreal, Quebec]].\n\n== Important buildings ==\n*House For a Musician (1983)\n*House of the Suicide and House of the Mother of the Suicide (Prague, monument installed 2016)\n*Kreuzberg Tower and Wings (Berlin, Allemagne, 1988)\n*Tegel Housing (Berlin, 1988)\n*House of the Quadruplets / House for two Brothers (Berlin, Tegel, 1988)\n*Gate House (Berlin, 1991) for the IBA 87\n*La M\u00e1scara de la Medusa (Buenos Aires, 1998)\n*[[Wall House II]] (Groningen, 2001)\n\n<gallery heights=\"180\" widths=\"180\" caption=\"Important buildings of John Hejduk\">\nFile:HejdukKreuzbergTower1.jpg|Kreuzberg Tower and Wings<br /> (Berlin, Germany, 1988).\nFile:HejdukKreuzbergTower2.jpg|Kreuzberg Tower and Wings<br /> (Berlin, Germany, 1988).\nFile:Wall House2.JPG|Wall House [[Wall House II|II]]<br /> design from the 1970s, built posthumously (Groningen, The Netherlands, 2001).\nFile:2013. Torres Hejduk. Cidade da Cultura. Santiago de Compostela - Galiza-2.jpg|In [[Santiago de Compostela]], Spain.\n</gallery>\n\n=== The Rolling House ===\nIn 2019, students of the Faculty of Architecture of the [[Czech Technical University]] in Prague led by Hana Seho built the object ''The Rolling House'' according to drawings by John Hejduk. The project was created in the studio during the Summer School of Building on the topic of minimal mobile building. The realization took place in October and November 2019. The building was unveiled on 11 November 2019 as a celebration of the 30th anniversary of the [[Velvet Revolution]] and as a gift to [[Alena \u0160r\u00e1mkov\u00e1]] for her 90th birthday.<ref>{{cite web\n |url= https://aktualne.cvut.cz/tiskove-zpravy/20191115-studenti-a-pedagogove-fakulty-architektury-cvut-v-praze-dali-alene-sramkove\n |title= 