alleged [[affair]] with Kobe Bryant apparently led to Vanessa Bryant filing for [[divorce]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thedirty.com/2013/03/was-melissa-satta-to-blame-for-kobe-bryants-failed-marriage/|title=Melissa Satta to blame for Kobe Bryant's failed marriage|access-date=28 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203004549/http://thedirty.com/2013/03/was-melissa-satta-to-blame-for-kobe-bryants-failed-marriage/|archive-date=3 December 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Satta began a relationship with footballer [[Kevin-Prince Boateng]]; the pair soon became engaged.<ref name=\"verissimo\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vanityfair.it/people/italia/2019/11/01/melissa-satta-boateng-crisi-matrimonio-figlio-vita-privata-gossip-foto-verissimo |title=Melissa Satta a \u00abVerissimo\u00bb: \u00abIl matrimonio \u00e8 sacrificio. Un altro figlio? C'\u00e8 tempo\u00bb |publisher=Vanity Fair |language=Italian |last1=Casiraghi |first1=Claudia |date=1 November 2019 |accessdate=12 November 2019 }}</ref> In April 2014, Satta had a child with her fianc\u00e9, called 'Maddox Prince',<ref>{{cite web|title=GC SportsKevin Prince Boateng & Fianc\u00e9e Melissa Satta Are Blessed with a Baby Boy-Maddox Prince Boateng!|url=https://www.ghanacelebrities.com/2014/04/16/kevin-prince-boateng-fiancee-melissa-satta-blessed-baby-boy-maddox-prince-boateng/|publisher=ghanacelebrities.com|accessdate=4 July 2017|date=16 April 2014}}</ref> then in June 2016, they married in [[Porto Cervo]], Sardinia.<ref>{{cite news|last1=BRENNAN|first1=SIOFRA|title=Ex-AC Milan player marries his model girlfriend in a lavish Sardinian ceremony with TWO wedding dresses, Tiffany rings and a surprise gig by Andrea Bocelli|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/femail/article-3665941/Ex-AC-Milan-player-Kevin-Prince-Boateng-maries-Melissa-Satta.html|accessdate=4 July 2017|work=Daily Mail|date=29 June 2016}}</ref> The pair separated in January 2019, before reuniting later that year.<ref name=\"verissimo\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" | Film\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2007\n| ''[[:it:Il giudice Mastrangelo|Judge Mastrangelo 2]]''\n| Cameo\n| directed by [[:it:Henry Oldoini|Henry Oldoini]] - Miniseries TV\n|-\n| ''[[:it:Bastardi|Bastardi]]''\n| Cameo\n| Italian film directed by Federico Del Zoppo and Andres Alce Meldonado\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" | Television\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''Mio fratello \u00e8 Pakistano (My brother is)''\n| Herself\n| Television program broadcast by [[Canale 5]]\n|-\n| 2005\u20132008\n| ''[[:it:Striscia la notizia|Striscia la notizia]] (The news)''\n| Presenter\n| 2005-2008, vellum, Canale 5\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Total Request Live (Italy)|TRL (Italy)]]''\n| Presenter\n| Italian version of the MTV Television reality program\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''White Party Fashion TV''\n| Presenter\n| [[Fashion TV]]\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[:it:Primo e ultimo|First and last]]''\n| Presenter\n| Italian TV program on [[:it:Italia 1|Italy 1]], presented with [[:it:Teo Mammucari|Teo Mammucari]]\n|-\n| 2009\u20132010\n| ''[[:it:Controcampo (programma televisivo)|Controcampo (TV)]]''\n| Presenter\n| Italian Television talk show on [[Rete 4]], presented with [[:it:Alberto Brandi|Alberto Brandi]]\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''Uno scandalo al sole (A scandal in the sun)''\n| Presenter\n| \n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[:it:Fenomenal|Fenomenal]]''\n| Guest\n| Italian TV program on [[:it:Italia 1|Italy 1]], presented by [[:it:Teo Mammucari|Teo Mammucari]]\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[:it:Lasciami cantare!|Let me sing!]]''\n| Guest\n| \n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Insideout, Pazzi per la scienza''\n| Presenter\n| presenter of the Italian version of [[BBC Two]]'s \"Crazy for science\"\n|-\n| 2011\u20132012\n| ''[[:it:Kalisp\u00e9ra|Kalispera]]''\n| Presenter\n| Italian TV program on [[Canale 5]], presented with [[:it:Alfonso Signorini|Alfonso Signorini]]\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[:it:Punto su di te!|Punto su di te!]]''\n| Presenter\n| Italian TV program on [[Rai 1]], presented with [[Elisa Isoardi]]\n|-\n| 2012\u20132013\n| ''Intitolata Amici a letto (Friends in bed)''\n| Herself\n| Italian Sitcom TV program on [[Comedy Central Italy]]/[[Comedy Central]], starred with [[:it:Omar Fantini|Omar Fantini]]\n|-\n| 2013\u20132014\n| ''TikiTaka''\n| Presenter\n| Italian [[Broadcasting of sports events|TV sports program]] on [[Italia 1]]/[[Mediaset Italia]], [[Mediaset]], presented with [[Pierluigi Pardo]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" | Advertisement\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Peugeot]]''\n| Herself\n| advertisement for Peugeot's 107 Petite plague\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{FMD model}}\n\n{{2010\u20132019 Sports Illustrated Swimsuit}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Satta, Melissa}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Sardinian descent]]\n[[Category:American showgirls]]\n[[Category:Communication scholars]]\n[[Category:American television hosts]]\n[[Category:American women in business]]\n[[Category:University of Milan alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Boston]]\n[[Category:People from Cagliari]]\n[[Category:Footballers' wives and girlfriends]]\n[[Category:Women television presenters]]\n[[Category:American karateka]]\n", "name_user": "Astrolabbio", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melissa_Satta"}
{"title_page": "Pertti Salolainen", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n'''Pertti Edvard Salolainen''' [[CBE]]<ref name=cbeverkkouutiset>{{cite web |url=https://www.verkkouutiset.fi/pertti-salolaiselle-britannian-korkea-arvonimi/ |title=Pertti Salolaiselle Britannian korkea arvonimi\n|last=|first= |date=|website=|publisher =Verkkouutiset |access-date=|quote= }}</ref> (born 19 October 1940 [[Helsinki]]) is a Finnish politician. He has served as MP from the [[National Coalition Party]] (1970\u20131996, 2007\u20132019) and party chairman (1991\u20131994) and Minister (1987\u20131995).<ref name=\"eduskunta\">[https://www.eduskunta.fi/FI/kansanedustajat/Sivut/259.aspx Pertti Salolainen] Parliament of Finland (in Finnish). Retrieved 29 December 2016.</ref>\n\nSalolainen worked before the MP career in [[Yle|Finnish Broadcasting Company]] between 1962\u20131969 as a journalist and producer. Between 1996 and 2004, he was the [[Embassy of Finland, London|Finnish Ambassador in London]].<ref name=eduskunta/>\n\n== Career ==\n\nSalolainen was born on 19 October 1940 in Helsinki during the [[Interim Peace]] period to the family of sergeant Edvard Salolainen and the shopkeeper Ella Salolainen (n\u00e9e ''Lundqvist'')\n\nHe graduated as Master of Science in Economics from the [[Aalto University School of Business|Helsinki School of Economics]] in 1969.\n\nSalolainen began his career as a [[Finnish Broadcasting Company]]'s television newsreader and editor in 1962\u20131965. He was a producer of Finnish Broadcasting Company's financial programs from 1965 to 1966, [[BBC World Service]] [[Finnish language]] editorial editor in London in 1966 and Finnish Broadcasting Company's correspondent in London from 1966 to 1969.<ref name=eduskunta/>\n\n==Politics==\n\nSalolainen was elected to the [[Parliament of Finland]] for the first time in the [[1970 Finnish parliamentary election|1970 parliamentary elections]]. In Parliament, he served as Deputy Chairman of the Social Committee (1970\u20131975) and Chairman of the Finance Committee (1979\u20131987). Salolainen was also a member of the [[Helsinki City Council]] between 1972 and 1984.<ref name=eduskunta/>\n\nSalolainen served as Minister for Foreign Affairs in the [[Holkeri Cabinet|Holkeri Government]], and Minister of Trade and Industry (Foreign Trade Minister) in 1987\u20131991.<ref name=ministeri>{{cite web |url= http://valtioneuvosto.fi/tietoa/historiaa/hallitukset-ja-ministerit/raportti/-/r/m2/77 |title=Ministerin tiedot: Salolainen, Pertti Edvard|website=|publisher=Valtioneuvosto }}</ref>\n\nHe was a questioned publicity in 1989, being visiting China as the first Western official guest after the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|massacre of Tiananmein Square]]. The decision to travel to China was made by the government and had the approval from President [[Mauno Koivisto]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fi.gbtimes.com/politiikka/suomi-ja-kiina-60-vuotta-kumppanuutta |title=Suomi ja Kiina \u2013 60 vuotta kumppanuutta |last=Suokas|first= Janne |website=|publisher=GBTimes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.savonsanomat.fi/paakirjoitukset/Pallo-omassa-nilkassa/500403  |title=Pallo omassa nilkassa |last=Liukkonen|first=Mauri  |website=|publisher=Savon Sanomat}}</ref>\n\nSalolainen continued as Foreign Trade Minister and Deputy Prime Minister between 1991 and 1995 in the [[Aho Cabinet|Aho Government]]<ref name=ministeri/> In the early 1990s, he was responsible for the Finnish membership negotiations in the [[European Union]].<ref name=\"IL\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iltalehti.fi/uutiset/2011011112985922_uu.shtml |title=EU-j\u00e4senyydest\u00e4 neuvotellut Salolainen: Sain tappouhkauksia|last=Tanner|first= Matti |website=|publisher=Iltalehti}}</ref>\n\nSalolainen was Chairman of the [[European Economic Area]]'s negotiating delegation from 1990 to 1993 and chairman of the Finnish EU negotiating delegation and negotiating minister 1993\u20131995.<ref name=\"eduskunta\" />\n\nSalolainen has later told that he and other ministers had gotten death treats at the time, when Finland negotiated the membership in the EU. He has told later that he was under the protection of [[Finnish Security Intelligence Service]] because the death threats were considered serious.<ref name=\"IL\" />\n\nIn 1991 Salolainen was elected as the Chairman of the National Coalition Party after [[Ilkka Suominen]]. He was in charged until 1994 when he was succeeded by [[Sauli Niinist\u00f6]]. Salolainen left the Parliament in October 1996 after he was appointed as the Finland's Ambassador to London. He Ambassador under 2004. He was replaced in Parliament by [[Pirjo-Riitta Antvuori]].<ref name=\"eduskunta\" />\n\n===Return to politics in 2004===\nIn the [[2007 Finnish parliamentary election|2007 parliamentary elections]], Salolainen became a candidate, by the wish from party's chairman [[Jyrki Katainen]], from Helsinki, even though he had already refused the candidacy\n\nHe returned to the Parliament from Helsinki as National Coalition Party's candidate with the fourth highest number of votes (8,621 votes)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iltasanomat.fi/uutiset/kotimaa/uutinen.asp?id=1307981 |title=Pertti Salolainen sittenkin vaaleihin |last=Anttila|first=  Timo J. |website=|publisher=Ilta Sanomat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://tulospalvelu.vaalit.fi/E2007/s/valitut/helsinkivpval.htm |title= Eduskuntavaalit 18.3.2007: Valitut ehdokkaat Helsingin vaalipiiri |website=|publisher=Oikeusministeri\u00f6 }}</ref> In his previous election, Salolainen had been the highest vote getter.\n\nIn the 2011 parliamentary elections, Salolainen was elected for a further term of 6, 205 votes\n<ref>{{cite web |url= http://tulospalvelu.vaalit.fi/E2011/s/valitut/helsinkivpval.htm |title= Eduskuntavaalit 17.4.20011: Valitut ehdokkaat Helsingin vaalipiiri |website=|publisher=Oikeusministeri\u00f6 }}</ref>\n\n== Confessions==\nSalolainen has long been involved in the [[World Wide Fund for Nature|WWF]]. He served as the Supervisory Board of the WWF's Finnish Fund and the Vice-Chairman of the Fund from 1972 to 1989.<ref name=\"eduskunta\"/><ref name=\"BBB\">{{cite web |url=http://www.perttisalolainen.fi/fi/Curriculum/ |title=Curriculum |website=|publisher=Pertti Salolainen}}</ref>\n\n[[City of London|London City]] granted Salolainen the [[List of Honorary Freemen of the City of London|Honorary Freemen of the City of London]] status in 1998. In Finland, he was awarded the Minister honorary title in 2004. Salolainen has also been awarded [[Order of the Lion of Finland]] and the [[Finnish Association for Nature Conservation]]'s golden badge<ref name=\"eduskunta\"/><ref name=\"BBB\"/>\n\nIn 2017 Queen Elizabeth II awarded Salolainen as [[CBE]]<ref name=cbeverkkouutiset/>\n\n== Allegation of anti-Semitism==\n\nIn 2012, Salolainen said on a television program that the United States cannot take a neutral stance on the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict]] due to the influence of the [[American Jews]]. The [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] demanded him to be removed from office because of this comment. According to the Center, Salolainen reiterated \"an anti-Semitic story about Jewish secret societies. Salolainen denied that his comment was [[anti-Semitism|anti-Semitic]].<ref>[http://www.iltalehti.fi/uutiset/2012120116398359_uu.shtml Suomalaispoliitikon kommentti suututti juutalaiset] ''[[Iltalehti]]'' on 1 December 2012. Retrieved 29 December 2016.</ref>\n\n== Sources ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.perttisalolainen.fi Pertti Salolainen's website]\n* [https://www.eduskunta.fi/EN/kansanedustajat/Pages/259.aspx Pertti Salolainen on the website of the Parliament (in English)]\n\n{{NationalCoalitionPartyLeaders}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salolainen, Pertti}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Helsinki]]\n[[Category:National Coalition Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Finland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1970\u201372)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1972\u201375)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1975\u201379)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1979\u201383)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1983\u201387)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1987\u201391)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1991\u201395)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1995\u201399)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2007\u201311)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2011\u201315)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2015\u201319)]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Finnish reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:BBC newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:Honorary Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Cross of Terra Mariana, 2nd Class]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n'''Pertti Edvard Salolainen''' [[CBE]]<ref name=cbeverkkouutiset>{{cite web |url=https://www.verkkouutiset.fi/pertti-salolaiselle-britannian-korkea-arvonimi/ |title=Pertti Salolaiselle Britannian korkea arvonimi\n|last=|first= |date=|website=|publisher =Verkkouutiset |access-date=|quote= }}</ref> (born 19 October 1940 [[Helsinki]]) is a Finnish politician. He has served as MP from the [[National Coalition Party]] (1970\u20131996, 2007\u20132019) and party chairman (1991\u20131994) and Minister (1987\u20131995).<ref name=\"eduskunta\">[https://www.eduskunta.fi/FI/kansanedustajat/Sivut/259.aspx Pertti Salolainen] Parliament of Finland (in Finnish). Retrieved 29 December 2016.</ref>\n\nSalolainen worked before the MP career in [[Yle|Finnish Broadcasting Company]] between 1962\u20131969 as a journalist and producer. Between 1996 and 2004, he was the [[Embassy of Finland, London|Finnish Ambassador in London]].<ref name=eduskunta/>\n\n== Career ==\n\nSalolainen was born on 19 October 1940 in Helsinki during the [[Interim Peace]] period to the family of sergeant Edvard Salolainen and the shopkeeper Ella Salolainen (n\u00e9e ''Lundqvist'')\n\nHe graduated as Master of Science in Economics from the [[Aalto University School of Business|Helsinki School of Economics]] in 1969.\n\nSalolainen began his career as a [[Finnish Broadcasting Company]]'s television newsreader and editor in 1962\u20131965. He was a producer of Finnish Broadcasting Company's financial programs from 1965 to 1966, [[BBC World Service]] [[Finnish language]] editorial editor in London in 1966 and Finnish Broadcasting Company's correspondent in London from 1966 to 1969.<ref name=eduskunta/>\n\n==Politics==\n\nSalolainen was elected to the [[Parliament of Finland]] for the first time in the [[1970 Finnish parliamentary election|1970 parliamentary elections]]. In Parliament, he served as Deputy Chairman of the Social Committee (1970\u20131975) and Chairman of the Finance Committee (1979\u20131987). Salolainen was also a member of the [[Helsinki City Council]] between 1972 and 1984.<ref name=eduskunta/>\n\nSalolainen served as Minister for Foreign Affairs in the [[Holkeri Cabinet|Holkeri Government]], and Minister of Trade and Industry (Foreign Trade Minister) in 1987\u20131991.<ref name=ministeri>{{cite web |url= http://valtioneuvosto.fi/tietoa/historiaa/hallitukset-ja-ministerit/raportti/-/r/m2/77 |title=Ministerin tiedot: Salolainen, Pertti Edvard|website=|publisher=Valtioneuvosto }}</ref>\n\nHe was a questioned publicity in 1989, being visiting China as the first Western official guest after the [[Tiananmen Square protests of 1989|massacre of Tiananmein Square]]. The decision to travel to China was made by the government and had the approval from President [[Mauno Koivisto]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fi.gbtimes.com/politiikka/suomi-ja-kiina-60-vuotta-kumppanuutta |title=Suomi ja Kiina \u2013 60 vuotta kumppanuutta |last=Suokas|first= Janne |website=|publisher=GBTimes}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.savonsanomat.fi/paakirjoitukset/Pallo-omassa-nilkassa/500403  |title=Pallo omassa nilkassa |last=Liukkonen|first=Mauri  |website=|publisher=Savon Sanomat}}</ref>\n\nSalolainen continued as Foreign Trade Minister and Deputy Prime Minister between 1991 and 1995 in the [[Aho Cabinet|Aho Government]]<ref name=ministeri/> In the early 1990s, he was responsible for the Finnish membership negotiations in the [[European Union]].<ref name=\"IL\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iltalehti.fi/uutiset/2011011112985922_uu.shtml |title=EU-j\u00e4senyydest\u00e4 neuvotellut Salolainen: Sain tappouhkauksia|last=Tanner|first= Matti |website=|publisher=Iltalehti}}</ref>\n\nSalolainen was Chairman of the [[European Economic Area]]'s negotiating delegation from 1990 to 1993 and chairman of the Finnish EU negotiating delegation and negotiating minister 1993\u20131995.<ref name=\"eduskunta\" />\n\nSalolainen has later told that he and other ministers had gotten death treats at the time, when Finland negotiated the membership in the EU. He has told later that he was under the protection of [[Finnish Security Intelligence Service]] because the death threats were considered serious.<ref name=\"IL\" />\n\nIn 1991 Salolainen was elected as the Chairman of the National Coalition Party after [[Ilkka Suominen]]. He was in charged until 1994 when he was succeeded by [[Sauli Niinist\u00f6]]. Salolainen left the Parliament in October 1996 after he was appointed as the Finland's Ambassador to London. He Ambassador under 2004. He was replaced in Parliament by [[Pirjo-Riitta Antvuori]].<ref name=\"eduskunta\" />\n\n===Return to politics in 2004===\nIn the [[2007 Finnish parliamentary election|2007 parliamentary elections]], Salolainen became a candidate, by the wish from party's chairman [[Jyrki Katainen]], from Helsinki, even though he had already refused the candidacy\n\nHe returned to the Parliament from Helsinki as National Coalition Party's candidate with the fourth highest number of votes (8,621 votes)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iltasanomat.fi/uutiset/kotimaa/uutinen.asp?id=1307981 |title=Pertti Salolainen sittenkin vaaleihin |last=Anttila|first=  Timo J. |website=|publisher=Ilta Sanomat}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://tulospalvelu.vaalit.fi/E2007/s/valitut/helsinkivpval.htm |title= Eduskuntavaalit 18.3.2007: Valitut ehdokkaat Helsingin vaalipiiri |website=|publisher=Oikeusministeri\u00f6 }}</ref> In his previous election, Salolainen had been the highest vote getter.\n\nIn the 2011 parliamentary elections, Salolainen was elected for a further term of 6, 205 votes\n<ref>{{cite web |url= http://tulospalvelu.vaalit.fi/E2011/s/valitut/helsinkivpval.htm |title= Eduskuntavaalit 17.4.20011: Valitut ehdokkaat Helsingin vaalipiiri |website=|publisher=Oikeusministeri\u00f6 }}</ref>\n\n== Confessions==\nSalolainen has long been involved in the [[World Wide Fund for Nature|WWF]]. He served as the Supervisory Board of the WWF's Finnish Fund and the Vice-Chairman of the Fund from 1972 to 1989.<ref name=\"eduskunta\"/><ref name=\"BBB\">{{cite web |url=http://www.perttisalolainen.fi/fi/Curriculum/ |title=Curriculum |website=|publisher=Pertti Salolainen}}</ref>\n\n[[City of London|London City]] granted Salolainen the [[List of Honorary Freemen of the City of London|Honorary Freemen of the City of London]] status in 1998. In Finland, he was awarded the Minister honorary title in 2004. Salolainen has also been awarded [[Order of the Lion of Finland]] and the [[Finnish Association for Nature Conservation]]'s golden badge<ref name=\"eduskunta\"/><ref name=\"BBB\"/>\n\nIn 2017 Queen Elizabeth II awarded Salolainen as [[CBE]]<ref name=cbeverkkouutiset/>\n\n== Allegation of anti-Semitism==\n\nIn 2012, Salolainen said on a television program that the United States cannot take a neutral stance on the [[Israeli\u2013Palestinian conflict]] due to the influence of the [[American Jews]]. The [[Simon Wiesenthal Center]] demanded him to be removed from office because of this comment. According to the Center, Salolainen reiterated \"an anti-Semitic story about Jewish secret sociaties. Salolainen denied that his comment was [[anti-Semitism|anti-Semitic]].<ref>[http://www.iltalehti.fi/uutiset/2012120116398359_uu.shtml Suomalaispoliitikon kommentti suututti juutalaiset] ''[[Iltalehti]]'' on 1 December 2012. Retrieved 29 December 2016.</ref>\n\n== Sources ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* [http://www.perttisalolainen.fi Pertti Salolainen's website]\n* [https://www.eduskunta.fi/EN/kansanedustajat/Pages/259.aspx Pertti Salolainen on the website of the Parliament (in English)]\n\n{{NationalCoalitionPartyLeaders}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salolainen, Pertti}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Helsinki]]\n[[Category:National Coalition Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Finland]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1970\u201372)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1972\u201375)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1975\u201379)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1979\u201383)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1983\u201387)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1987\u201391)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1991\u201395)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (1995\u201399)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2007\u201311)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2011\u201315)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Finland (2015\u201319)]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Finnish reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:BBC newsreaders and journalists]]\n[[Category:Honorary Commanders of the O